nd","Haughton, Staffordshire, England":"Haughton, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1502–1560":"about 1502–1560","1504–1525":"1504–1525","1524–1585":"1524–1585","1624–1634":"1624–1634","1502–1560":"1502–1560","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1624":"1624","1524":"1524","1502":"1502","1634":"1634","1585":"1585","about 1502":"about 1502","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Haughton, Staffordshire, England":"Haughton, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hodges","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hodge   with genitival or post-medieval <i>-s</i>. Occasionally, however, the name may be topographic for a person who lived or worked at the house of someone named <i>Hodge</i> or <i>Roger</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hodge","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hogge</i>, a rhyming pet form of   Roger  . In <i>The Canterbury Tales</i>, Chaucer's cook, ‘highte <i>Hogge</i> of Ware’, is invoked ‘Now tell on, <i>Roger</i> …’. Since Middle English spellings of the personal name are often impossible to distinguish from the nickname <i>Hog(ge)</i> ‘hog’, some early examples may be variants of   Hogg  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":47,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":56,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Hodges was born about 1502, in Haughton, Staffordshire, England. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Margaret Fisher. He died in 1560, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"about 1502–1560":"umbes 1502–1560","1504–1525":"1504–1525","1524–1585":"1524–1585","1624–1634":"1624–1634","1502–1560":"1502–1560","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1624":"1624","1524":"1524","1502":"1502","1634":"1634","1585":"1585","about 1502":"umbes 1502","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Haughton, Staffordshire, England":"Haughton, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1502–1560":"noin 1502–1560","1504–1525":"1504–1525","1524–1585":"1524–1585","1624–1634":"1624–1634","1502–1560":"1502–1560","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1624":"1624","1524":"1524","1502":"1502","1634":"1634","1585":"1585","about 1502":"noin 1502","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Haughton, Staffordshire, England":"Haughton, Staffordshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1502–1560":"environ 1502–1560","1504–1525":"1504–1525","1524–1585":"1524–1585","1624–1634":"1624–1634","1502